SIMPLE: mighty
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mighty
<hw>Might"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Mightier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Mightiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>meahtig</ets>,
<ets>mihtig</ets>; akin to G. <ets>m⟦aum⟧chtig</ets>, Goth.
<ets>mahteigs</ets>. See <er>Might</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Possessing might; having great power or
authority.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wise in heart, and <qex>mighty</qex> in strength.</q> <rj><qau>Job
ix. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Accomplished by might; hence, extraordinary;
wonderful.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧His <xex>mighty</xex> works.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Matt. xi. 20.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Denoting an extraordinary degree or quality in
respect of size, character, importance, consequences, etc.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>mighty</xex> famine.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Luke xv. 14.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧Giants of <xex>mighty</xex> bone.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Milton.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Mighty</qex> was their fuss about little matters.</q>
<rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mighty</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mighty
<hw>Might"y</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mighties</plw>
<pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <def>A warrior of great force and courage.</def>
<mark>[R. & Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>1 Chron. xi. 12.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mighty</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mighty
<hw>Might"y</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a great degree; very.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧He was <xex>mighty</xex>
methodical.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Jeffrey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We have a <qex>mighty</qex> pleasant garden.</q>
<rj><qau>Doddridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Migniard</ent>⟦br⟧
